SIMPLE: rebel
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rebel
<hw>Reb"el</hw> <pr>(r⟦ecr⟧b"⟦ecr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>rebelle</ets>, fr. L. <ets>rebellis</ets>. See <er>Rebel</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>Pertaining to rebels or rebellion; acting
in revolt; rebellious; <as>as, <ex>rebel</ex> troops</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whoso be <qex>rebel</qex> to my judgment.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Convict by flight, and <qex>rebel</qex> to all law.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rebel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rebel
<hw>Reb"el</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>rebelle</ets>.]</ety>
<def>One who rebels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Revolter; insurgent.</syn> <usage> --
<er>Rebel</er>, <er>Insurgent</er>. <xex>Insurgent</xex> marks an early,
and <xex>rebel</xex> a more advanced, stage of opposition to government.
The former rises up against his rulers, the latter makes war upon
them.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rebel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rebel
<hw>Re*bel"</hw> <pr>(r⟦esl⟧*b⟦ecr⟧l")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Rebelled</conjf>
<pr>(r⟦esl⟧*b⟦ecr⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rebelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>rebeller</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>rebellare</ets> to make war again; pref. <ets>re-</ets> again +
<ets>bellare</ets> to make war, fr. <ets>bellum</ets> war. See
<er>Bellicose</er>, and cf. <er>Revel</er> to carouse.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To renounce, and resist by force, the authority of the
ruler or government to which one owes obedience. See
<er>Rebellion</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The murmur and the churls' <qex>rebelling</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye have builded you an altar, that ye might <qex>rebel</qex> this
day against the Lord.</q> <rj><qau>Josh. xxii. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be disobedient to authority; to assume a hostile
or insubordinate attitude; to revolt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How could my hand <qex>rebel</qex> against my heart?⟦br⟧
How could your heart <qex>rebel</qex> against your reason?</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rebeldom</ent>⟦br⟧
